-- Field Journal pen: Sanna Kivelä (Gear desk). Summer 2026 batch.
insert into public.blog_posts (
  slug, title, kicker, excerpt, category_slug, tags, hero_image, hero_alt,
  content, author_id, author_snapshot, status, published_at, featured,
  read_time_minutes
) values (
  'what-july-in-lapland-actually-asks-you-to-pack',
  'What July in Lapland actually asks you to pack',
  'Gear desk · July · Packing',
  'Ten days in the north with one duffel bag: what earned its place, what failed in the field, and the three cheap items that outperformed everything with a logo. A packing report from the warm end of the Lapland year.',
  'gear',
  ARRAY['gear','packing','summer','mosquitoes']::text[],
  '/images/summer-gear-porch-1200.webp',
  'Backpack, rain shell, mosquito head net and thermos laid out on weathered wooden cabin porch boards',
  '[{"type":"paragraph","text":"Everything you need to know about packing for Lapland in July is contained in one weather report. On the middle Saturday of my last trip it was twenty-six degrees and cloudless at two in the afternoon, and I swam in a lake and regretted bringing so many clothes. That same night, on open ground further up the road, it was eight degrees with a wind that meant it, and I wore everything I owned at once, including the swimming towel as a scarf. Neither of those days was unusual. That is simply the range July offers, sometimes within one Tuesday, and your bag has to answer for all of it."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"This desk works on a simple accounting method: after each trip, everything in the bag gets sorted into three piles — earned its place, tolerated, and should have stayed home. What follows is the July audit, ten days, one sixty-litre duffel, cabins and day trails, no resupply drama because in Finland there is always a supermarket within an hour and it is better stocked than yours at home. Nobody needs to pack like the Arctic is a moon base. The Arctic has K-Markets."},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"The pile that earned its place"},{"type":"list","items":["A real rain shell with a hood, not a fashion one. July rain up here arrives sideways and leaves without apologising. The shell doubles as the wind layer on the fells, which is where it did most of its shifts.","One warm mid layer — mine is a fleece older than some of my colleagues. It was on my body every single night of the trip, including the ones that began at twenty-six degrees.","The mosquito head net. Eleven grams, costs less than an airport coffee, and there is an hour in a birch bog near Kittilä during which I would not have sold mine for a hundred euros. You will look ridiculous. Everyone looks ridiculous. The mosquitoes have seen it all before.","Repellent bought in Finland, from a Finnish pharmacy or supermarket shelf. The local formulas are tuned to the local opposition. I carry one bottle and top up on arrival like everyone else.","A sleep mask. The sun does not set in early July and not every cabin has serious curtains. This is the highest value-to-weight object in the entire bag and it is not close.","Trail shoes plus rubber sandals, and nothing else on the shoe front. The shoes do the fells, the sandals do the dock, the sauna path, the midnight yard, and the drive. Leather anything stayed home and was not missed.","A thin wool hat and thin gloves. In July. I know. Ask the person on the fell at one in the morning how funny it is.","A sit pad, foam, one euro of material. Wet stone, dew-soaked dock, prickly forest floor — it worked more hours than the camera did.","A thermos. Coffee on a fell at midnight is worth double coffee anywhere else, and the thermos also carried cold lake-cooled juice on the hot afternoons. Both directions of temperature, one cylinder."]},{"type":"pullquote","text":"Pack for a country where afternoon and midnight are two different climates and the supermarket is never far."},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"The pile that failed"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"The failures deserve names, because the failures are where the money went. The cotton hoodie: soaked one evening of dew and then spent four days as a damp regret hanging from a nail, teaching me the lesson wool people have been smug about for a century. The second pair of jeans: never left the duffel, weighs as much as a filled thermos, carried a thousand kilometres for nothing. The elaborate camera bag with modular dividers: the camera lived in a wool sock inside the daypack the whole trip, which is where it has always been happiest. And the expensive quick-dry travel towel that smells like a wet dog after two uses — outperformed, decisively, by the cheap thin cotton sauna towel bought at a village shop for seven euros, which dried on the porch rail in an hour like it was designed for exactly this life, because it was."},{"type":"paragraph","text":"I also packed, and I confess this in the interest of full disclosure, a paper map for an area I then explored entirely on marked and signposted day trails. The map is not a failure exactly — the map is insurance, and insurance is allowed to be boring — but let the record show the phone and the trail signs did the actual navigating, and the map saw daylight once, as a fan, during the hot Saturday."},{"type":"image","src":"/images/summer-gear-porch-1200.webp","alt":"Backpack, rain shell, mosquito head net and thermos laid out on weathered wooden cabin porch boards","caption":"The audit, laid out on the porch on the last morning. Everything pictured earned its place. The jeans are not pictured. The jeans know what they did.","full":true},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"The July system, in one paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"Think in thin layers that stack: something next to the skin that is not cotton, one warm thing, one shell that stops wind and rain, and legs that dry fast. Add the small comfort objects that northern life actually runs on — mask, net, sit pad, thermos — and stop. The days will be warmer than you expect and the nights will be colder than you believe, and the distance between those two facts is crossed by putting layers on and taking them off, sometimes six times in an evening, usually on a dock."},{"type":"heading","level":2,"text":"The last morning audit"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"On the final porch, repacking the duffel, I did the count. Earned its place: fourteen items. Tolerated: six. Should have stayed home: four, of which two were denim. The bag went home two kilos lighter in wisdom and exactly as heavy in fact, because on the last market morning I filled the freed-up space with a box of strawberries and two bags of salted liquorice, and I stand by both decisions the way the fleece stood by me."},{"type":"divider"},{"type":"paragraph","text":"Written at the departures gate at Rovaniemi airport, wearing the fleece, next to a duffel that smells faintly of birch whisk and woodsmoke, which no detergent should ever be allowed to fix."}]'::jsonb,
  NULL,
  '{"handle":"sanna","display_name":"Sanna Kivelä","avatar_url":null}'::jsonb,
  'published',
  '2026-07-07'::timestamptz,
  false,
  7
)
